This article provides an overview of Judge Neil M. Gorsuch, who served as a federal judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit for over a decade. He is described as a brilliant jurist with an outstanding intellect and a clear writing style. He is respected for his integrity, fairness, and understanding of the role of judges in interpreting the law rather than imposing their own policy preferences. Gorsuch is a native Westerner and enjoys outdoor activities such as fishing, hiking, and skiing. He has extensive professional experience, including trial and appellate litigation as a practicing attorney and serving in the Department of Justice as the Principal Deputy Associate Attorney General. He has impeccable academic credentials, having attended Harvard Law School and Oxford University as a Marshall Scholar. Gorsuch clerked for Justice Byron White, Justice Anthony Kennedy, and Judge David Sentelle. He is described as a "judge's judge" who decides cases based on the law rather than personal policy preferences. Gorsuch was confirmed by the U.S. Senate in 2006 without opposition and received a "unanimously well qualified rating" by the American Bar Association.